
[1]den

   DEN, n.

   1. A cave or hollow place in the earth; usually applied to a cave, pit,
   or subterraneous recess, used for concealment, shelter, protection or
   security; as a lions den; a den of robbers or thieves.

   The beasts go into dens. The children of Israel made themselves dens.
   Job 37. Judges 6.

   2. As a termination, in names of places, it denotes the place to be in
   a valley or near a wood.

                       DEN, v.i. To dwell as in a den.
